column66: Provision of Home to School Bus Transport Services to the Two Counties Trust
column67:
It is a challenging time for funding within the UK Education Sector. As a Multi-Academy Trust (MAT) receiving funding directly from the government, The Two Counties Trust (TTCT) must
      be able to show that it has commercial arrangements in place to deliver value for money and to secure continuous improvement in how it carries out its work. As a result, TTCT is
      undertaking a competitive tender process for The Trust's Home to School Bus Transport services as detailed within the Invitation to Tender (ITT) documents and associated Schedules.
      
      This Tender is comprised of 5 Lots. Each Lot is composed of Sub-Lots. Bidders are invited to bid for the Lots and/or Sub-Lots that they are able to service.
      
      For information the tender is split into the following 5 Lots (as detailed at Appendix B within the ITT documents):
      
      Lot 1 - Service Route 1 - Ashfield - split into Sub-Lots.
      Lot 2 - Service Route 2 - Friesland - split into Sub-Lots.
      Lot 3 - Service Route 3 - Heritage - split into Sub-Lots.
      Lot 4 - Service Route 4 - Selston - split into Sub-Lots.
      Lot 5 - Service Route 5 - Swanwick - split into Sub-Lots.
      
      ITT documentation is available via TTCTs procurement portal:

column67:
Preliminary Market Engagement (PME) for the potential installation of a Human Resources Information System at  London Luton Airport (Project: HiRise, procurement reference L24064).

Additional information: 
Not a contract notice / tender at this stage. A separate notice will go out should LLA look to progress with this project / proceed to issue a tender.

Please note that this Preliminary Market Engagement (PME) activity will not influence the evaluation of any subsequent tender and are purely to better inform the LLA project team. We may use information gathered at this stage to ensure that the project is market friendly and fit for purpose. Any information provided may be used to assist us in developing the tender and ensure that it allows all suppliers the opportunity to submit the best possible tender response that will lead to LLA selecting the solution that meets our requirements and needs. Suppliers needn't submit a response to this PME in order to bid for any subsequent tender.

To access this or any other LLA open PME / tender advert and to view the necessary documents and express your interest, please visit the LLA e-Tendering Portal at:

https://in-tendhost.co.uk/llaol

All tender and PME opportunities can be found under the Tenders link in the grey bar just below the LLA logo banner. If this is your first time using this portal, you will need to register in order to Express Interest by clicking the Register link also located in the grey bar or via the yellow Register button on the Home Screen.  If you are already registered on the LLA e-Tendering portal simply enter your details and login as usual.

During registration, simply complete the information required on the three areas Company Details, Business Classifications and Company Categories.  Once completed, click the Register My Company button located at the bottom.
  
Please note you must express an interest through this portal in order to be attached to the project.  After expressing interest and reviewing any PME documents, you will also be asked whether or not you wish to Opt In or Opt Out of the process and click the appropriate button. Doing so will indicate to the procurement team your intention to either make a submission or not.  Once you have opted in, you will be able to 'submit a response' via uploading documents, however for this PME stage you must use the Correspondence facility to ask any questions and respond with your timeslot/ written response. 

We accept no liability if you have not expressed an interest in this stage or any other PME / tenders.

Cashless System: Implementation of cashless payment options for laundry services. 

Refurbishments: Upgrading laundry rooms with new decor, fittings, flooring, and seating. 

Year-Round Operation: Ensuring continuous service with the ability to switch to free vend when needed. 

Flexibility: Adapting to changes in the university estate without extra costs. 

Pricing: Maintaining current pricing with a possible annual increase, subject to approval. 

Performance will be monitored through specific KPIs, including response times, maintenance schedules, and customer feedback.

column66: MEDWAY PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH AND PARENT-INFANT RELATIONSHIP STRATEGY AND WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT PROJECT
column67:
1.1	Medway Council is one of 75 eligible Local Authorities taking part in the Family Hubs and Start for Life programme in England https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/family-hubs-and-start-for-life-programme
1.2	The Family Hubs and Start for Life Programme is currently running until the end of March 2025. The funding which has been provided as part of the programme must be utilised before this date. 
1.3	There are specific requirements and timelines for delivering against aspects of the programme as set out in the Family Hubs and Start for Life framework and service expectations https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/family-hubs-and-start-for-life-programme-local-authority-guide.
1.4	The Local Authority is responsible for using the Family Hubs and Start for Life funding to improve provision of support for mild-to-moderate perinatal mental heath and parent-infant relationships. Moderate-to-severe (specialist) provision falls under the remit of Kent and Medway Integrated Care Board.
1.5	The Programme Guide (https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/62f0ef83e90e07142da01845/Family_Hubs_and_Start_for_Life_programme_guide.pdf) sets out an expectation for local areas to "establish a local perinatal and parent-infant mental health strategy (with sustainable plans beyond the funding period), to support strategic planning / delivery and joined-up working across the whole system"
1.6	A robust governance structure has already been established for PMH & PIR in Medway with commissioners and service leads meeting regularly to guide system improvements. However, a strategy has not yet been produced.
1.7	A number of services and interventions have already been commissioned using the funding provided. These include a PMH & PIR service with Family Action, baby massage training, singing therapy, a mental health web app, a mindful parenting programme and additional staff in maternity and health visiting teams. PIR training has not yet been fully commissioned and it is recognised that there is a need for development in this area.
1.8	As part of the Family Hubs and Start for Life Programme, a Parent-Carer Panel has been set up to encourage co-design and co-production of services. However, for PMH & PIR there is a need to engage more widely with seldom heard voices and research both the efficacy of current provision and how gaps can be best filled taking into account the diverse needs of Medway's population.

column65: Winchester District Digital Skills for Residents
column66: SOFT MARKET TESTING  FOR WINCHESTER DISTRICT DIGITAL SKILLS FOR RESIDENTS PROGRAMME
column67:
Winchester City Council is running a soft market testing to identify organisations who may be interested to quote for the upcoming Digital Skills for Winchester District Residents programme. 

The aim of the soft market testing is to: 
identify organisations who are not currently known to the council
give the council an understanding of any interest in the programme of work

For the avoidance of doubt, this notice is for the purpose of conducting a soft market testing exercise and will not formally begin the procurement or constitute any commitment by Winchester City Council to undertake any procurement exercise.

The purpose of this programme is to increase levels of digital inclusion and increase essential digital skills amongst the residents in the Winchester district. 

We would like the Digital Skills for Winchester District Residents programme to be delivered through:

one-to-one bespoke sessions based in the location where the resident is at a time that is convenient to them
workshop sessions visiting existing community groups - the community group can decide the theme to work on such as communicating online and internet safety
the completion of accredited Outlook or Office courses in a workshop setting.

Those using the service will be able to get help with, but not limited to:

internet safety (fraud and scam prevention)
understanding their device 
searching the internet to find information such as shop opening times, public transport timetables, sports, leisure and cultural activities, cooking recipes
sending and responding to emails
taking photographs
shopping online
using social media
booking medical appointments online, using e-consult and ordering prescriptions
using WhatsApp, iMessage, video calls, Facetime etc.

Residents will be able to self-refer, be referred from our partner organisations across the district and referred by the council's internal teams such as housing communities.

We require friendly trainers who will help with individual digital queries. Service users will bring real life queries, such as making a doctors appointment, and tasks the individual needs to do online. This programme of work will be taking place on a weekly basis, with several one-to-one mentor sessions, engagement with existing community groups and the accredited courses to be planned for every month, or when a full group of attendees are signed up and ready to go. The number of sessions, mentor sessions and courses is yet to be determined. 

Please see the full information in the attachment. 

Please return responses to our Sector Project Officer, Emily Reason at: ereason@winchester.gov.uk by 9am on Monday 10 June 2024.

column66: A59 Corridor Improvements
column67:
This procurement exercise is for the delivery of a Civil Engineering Works project; A59 Corridor Improvements on behalf of Sefton Council.  

The proposed scheme will comprise of a range of junction, cycleway, footway and highway improvement works along the A59 Northway in Maghull between the Dodds Lane junction and the West Lancashire borough boundary, approx. 1.5km to the north. The scheme will involve four main elements; modification to the Kenyons Lane junction with the introduction of a new CYCLOPS signal arrangement. Highway and footway works on Kenyons Lane. The creation of segregated cycle routes along both sides of the A59 and the continuation of the cycle routes around the junction with Robins Island including controlled push button facilitates for pedestrians and cyclists across the A59. 

The works will include footway, cycleway and highway surfacing, kerbing, street lighting, traffic signals and highway drainage, with traffic management required to undertake the works.

The A59 is a heavily used 'A road' linking Preston and Liverpool. The current speed limit of the A59 is 40-mph and 60-mph, with the higher speed limit north of Kenyons Lane through to the borough boundary. It is expected that the 60-mph limit will have been reduced to a permanent 40 mph prior to the Start Date.

column67:
Dunstable Town Council is seeking an organisation to provide an IT Support contract which includes management of our existing IT infrastructure, telephony, connectivity, and licencing. Further details are outlined below. 

It is important to the Council that a single supplier can provide the support, account management and billing for all services delivered. To aid service delivery there must be clear point of contacts for specific roles and responsibilities. 

The supplier may sub-contract delivery of certain areas if this is made clear in the tender response and that by sub-contracting it does not stop the organisation providing the single support, account management and billing required. column66: Provision of Notary Services for Complex International Legal Transactions for FCDO
column67:
The Foreign, Commonwealth & Development Office (the 'FCDO') - is the government department responsible for promoting British interests overseas and supporting our citizens and businesses around the globe. FCDO safeguard the UK's security, defend our values, reduce poverty and tackle global challenges with our international partners.

The FCDO has estate property around the world (including the United Kingdom) and operates in over 280 different locations. The estate comprises Embassies & High Commissions (anything from a stand-alone, freehold building on a secure compound, to a fitted-out leased office in a multi-occupied, high-rise building), visa offices, Residences for Heads of Post and residential buildings for diplomats. Additionally, there are individual "legacy" properties such as churches, cemeteries, etc.

To assist with the facilitation of acquiring, executing, and managing this estate, the Estates, Security and Network Directorate (ESND) of the FCDO, wish to appoint a Supplier to provide Notary Services. These services will support the authentication and drafting of legal documents for use in international contexts. The notary services for which the Tenderer is invited to tender for include but are not limited to, notarial services, powers of attorney, legalisation, acting and attesting within foreign languages and translation services.

The objectives of this contract are to:  
-	Establish a commercial arrangement with an experienced partner that provides value for money for the department by supporting the timely, wise, and effective management of the FCDO estate and that of its One HMG Partners (Other Government Departments and arms-length bodies) through the provision of notary services for complex international legal transactions. 
-	Establish a viable and resilient process that can deliver on the accurate and timely provision of notary services, ensuring no additional cost or time to the department.

The scope of services includes providing the following, in relation to the FCDO estate and those of its One HMG Partners; grant of power and delegated authority,
-	General legal advice, legal opinions, and guidance
-	Drafting appropriate supporting documentation for the acquisition, management and disposal of property interests 
-	Miscellaneous advice on UK, international and overseas local law
-       Advice and guidance on the intricacies and levels of complexity of each task
-	Translation services for legal documentation
-       Acting and advising in a Notary capacity in various languages and jurisdictions
-	Knowledge of the relevant legal procedures and mechanisms 
-	Notarial, certification and legalization services
-	Prompt and timely turnaround of all legal notarial documentation 
-	Arranging secure delivery of documents to UK and overseas addresses
-	Other ad hoc advice/services as advised 

The Contract will be for an initial 5 year period with an option to extend for up to a further 2 years.

column66: SE1113 - Research into Alternative/Parallel Sporting Structures
column67:
In January 2021 Sport England launched its ten-year Uniting the Movement Strategy ("UtM" or "the Strategy"), a collaborative vision to transform lives and communities through sport and physical activity (SPA) by causing change in the SPA sector and ecosystem, so that Sport England can work with stakeholders to give people the opportunities they need now and in the future to tackle the inequalities seen in sport and physical activity

As part of the 2022-25 Implementation Plan stage of the Strategy, Sport England seeks to change its offering to specifically target communities that have been traditionally left behind by collaborating with a more diverse set of partners to further identify, quantify, illuminate, and communicate the inequalities that exist in sport and physical activity and people's experiences, and has a requirement for research that identifies and illuminates what is successful and working well (i.e. bright spots) within alternative or parallel structures in supporting under-represented or marginalised groups to engage in sport and physical activity.

Sport England is appointing the supplier to conduct research on the role different forms of provision play in making the sport and physical activity sector more inclusive and accessible for different audiences and communities. The Supplier will deliver a diverse mix of in-depth case studies that explores the work and success of organisations operating in support of those communities, as well as the attitudes, experiences, and perspectives of the individuals and communities who engage with and benefit from their services.

column66: HE1851 B4069 Lyneham Banks Repair Wiltshire Council April 2024
column67:
B4069 Lyneham Banks Repairs \r
\r
In 2022 significant a significant landslip took place on the B4069 Lyneham in North Wiltshire. The resulting landslip dislodged around 90m of the existing carriageway downslope. The B4069 has been closed since February 2022 when the landslip took place, movements continued throughout the first part of 2022 until slowing significantly during the summer months. \r
 \r
The B4069 is a regionally important route providing connectivity between junction 17 of the M4 and North Wiltshire as well as serving several local communities. The road when opened normally takes around 5500 vehicles a day. \r
It is proposed to stabilise the slope with a contiguous piled embedded retaining wall with capping and upstand at the top. The proposed structure will be constructed on the northern side of the B4069 with a length of approximately 109m. \r
 \r
A in-situ reinforced concrete (RC) capping beam will be supported on a single row of 600 mm diameter bored concrete piles. The in-situ capping beam will be 1000 mm wide and 1500 mm deep structurally connected with the piles. The capping beam will be connected to tension micropiles to provide additional lateral ground support to the retaining wall.\r
 \r
A vertical infill parapet or edge restraint is also considered to be provided at this location. The new parapet may be installed in the verge or attached directly to the capping beam at the back of the verge. Highway works will include reinstatement of the carriageway, pavement, drainage, and kerbs. To provide improvement to the existing highway drainage system, it is proposed that the highway shall be drained by a combination of gullies, carrier/ collector pipes and catchpits. The proposed highway drainage will outfall to a watercourse north of the B4069 via a new culvert. \r
 \r
To ensure effective drainage of the site a number of land drainage measures will also be put in place on 3rd party land either side of the B4069. \r
 \r
The works will be designed and built in accordance with current standards and guidelines, and will include for all key aspects of highway construction - piling, earthworks, carriageway, drainage, signage, and hard and soft landscaping works.

column66: A New Community Centre
column67:
This project is concerned with the building of a new Community Centre within Elsenham on land that has been given to the Parish Council under a Section 106 agreement with a housing developer.  
The project is to be funded by a combination of S106 contributions from a series of developments within the village, together with other grant funding and potential borrowing from the Debt Management Office (formerly the Public Works Loan Board).
The new Community Centre is intended to provide facilities for this fast-growing village and the surrounding area.  It will be sited roughly in the centre of the village, and it is envisaged that it will become a true village centre and resource for the entire village.
The facilities should include:
A main hall capable of supporting events with 200 standing, or 120 seated at tables.  The hall does not need to be of sufficient height to accommodate badminton.  It should be possible to divide the hall into three meeting rooms through the use of folding partitions; 
Parish Council office and meeting space, approximately 10.0 metres X 5.0 metres, with separate access;
Small room for use to provide internet access, 3.0 metres X 3.0 metres;
A community caf with its own kitchen and seating area;
A community kitchen for users of the Centre;
changing facilities to Football Foundation standards incorporating direct access to the building and to the adjoining playing field;
Ample storage space, including provision for cleaning and maintenance;
Toilets with separate external access available.
Tender Submission
Tenders must be submitted strictly in accordance with the instructions.
A fee quotation should be submitted for the full design, project management and completion of this facility in accordance with the RIBA Stages of Work 2020.  It should be presented in the following format:
1.  Outline proposals for a potential scheme, including basic sketches of the vision for the development.
2.  Potential cost parameters for the scheme.
3.  Fee proposals associated with the scheme, which should be broken into the following stages:
a)	RIBA Stages  0  to 2.
b)	RIBA Stages  3 & 4.
c)	RIBA Stages  5 to 7.
   
The successful tenderer will be asked to make a public presentation in order to demonstrate the advantages of the scheme to the public.  This phase is regarded as key.  Personnel from the tenderer and from the Parish Council should be available to engage with the public and answer questions as required.
Tenders must be submitted by email to the Clerk to Elsenham Parish Council: louise.epc@gmail.com
Tenders must be submitted no later than 12:00 noon on 12 July 2024 which is the date fixed for the submission of tenders.  Tenders submitted after the deadline will not be accepted.
Tenders must be exclusive of Value Added Tax (VAT).

column66: Sustainable Estates and Facilities Solutions
column67:
This tender opportunity notice for Sustainable and Estates Facilities Solutions are covered under the Public Contracts Regulation (PCR) 2015.

NHS Commercial Solutions is seeking to procure, through a framework agreement, a panel of suitably experienced and qualified organisations to provide expert guidance and services to NHS organisations to assist them in delivering their commitments to a greener NHS and improving the healthcare environments.

Every NHS organisation is required to publish a Carbon Reduction Plan. Many of these plans include commitments to reduce carbon emissions in the organisation's built environments.

The Value at Risk to manageable assets in the UK, if we maintain a below 2 degrees of warming by 2045, is estimated to be more than 1 billion per annum, but we must prepare for warming up to 4 degrees. This includes increasing actions to reach net zero and increasing actions for resilience to the warming world. 

The purpose of the framework agreement is to offer industry specific opportunities for climate action, whilst building resilience to climate change, to enable the continuation of the delivery of healthcare services. 

The opportunities the agreement offers for healthcare which, in the context of the UN Sustainable Development Goals, represents the coming together of subject matter expertise, societal demands and climate action to create a more sustainable, inclusive, and future proof path to economic growth, health and well-being to support strategic initiatives of high impact for the benefit of business, people and the planet.

The services covered under the framework are: 
1 Environmental Consultancy
2A Sustainable Insulation
2B Natural Ventilation
2C Energy Efficient Windows and Doors
2D Heat Pumps/Passive Cooling Systems
2E Combined Heat and Power Systems
2F Rainwater Harvesting
2G Energy & Water Efficient Appliances
2H Energy-Efficient Lighting Systems
2I Solar Shading/Canopy Cover
2J Solar Film
3A Solar Power Generation and Storage
3B Wind Power Generation & Storage
4A Living Walls
4B Rainwater Gardens
4C Green Roof Spaces
4D Wellbeing Green Spaces

column66: The Growth Company Expression of Interest: Greater Manchester Combined Authority Level 3 Support
column67:
The Growth Company (GC) intends to bid as a Prime contractor for the Level 3 tender opportunity. GC is an existing prime provider operating in GM delivering Adult Skills programmes including Level 3. 

We are now inviting expressions of interests (EOI) from organisations who wish to deliver Level 3 provision within GM as part of our supply chain from 1st August 2024 to 31st July 2025.

GC is a social enterprise providing services to people, businesses, and places. Our people services include the delivery of employment, skills, health and justice-based contracts. Each year we help over 100,000 people to fulfil their potential.

We are seeking EOIs from experienced providers with a track record of delivering Level 3 programmes in Greater Manchester (GM) and with a well-established base in GM. We anticipate working with only 1 or 2 providers to deliver in-demand learning aligned to the needs of key sectors. GC is looking for end-to-end providers. 

Please download the documentation to view the opportunity and the key requirements. 

To apply for the EOI, you are required to make your submission via the Panacea e-tendering platform. Please register as a supplier on the Panacea Supplier Platform at the following web address: https://app.panacea-software.com/growth 
Once you have accessed the site, to view the opportunity you need to navigate to 'Register Interest', click the 'Participate' Button, then navigate to 'My Questionnaires' where you will be able to download the documents. Your EOI submission must be made on the Panacea Portal. The deadline for submission of the required documents is: 15:00pm on Friday 7th June 2024.

column66: Asset Based Community Development Study
column67: To undertake an Asset Based Community Development (ABCD) Study that will result in a strong evidence base that will inform activities and investment required to deliver against the Council's Community Plan, Health and Wellbeing Strategy, Housing Strategy and Economic Growth Strategy. The study will focus on a number of key areas within the Newark and Sherwood Local Authority District, The study will provide evidence to support future funding bids / applications to assist with the levelling up agenda and substantial information to develop a community engagement and regeneration plan and supports the creation of vibrant and self-sufficient local communities where residents look out for each other and actively contribute to their local area. Adopting the ABCD approach allows the council to develop a sustainable model for community development focused on the strengths and potential within a community. The project will develop our 'place based' working with partners to identify and develop a strengths-based register of community assets in a locality - covering both physical assets and individuals, groups and networks who contribute to sustainable, thriving communities.

column66: Provision of Ad Hoc Taxi Services
column67:
Bedford Borough Council (The Council) is often required to obtain transport at very short notice, including for young people and families due to unforeseen changes in circumstance. 
      
      The Council wishes to contract with taxi companies able to accept work when timelines preclude commissioning via our Passenger Transport Dynamic Purchasing System (DPS). These journeys will be instructed directly by officers, including in social work teams for a short period of time only. If the requirement is or becomes a long term one, the provision will be advertised on the Council Passenger Transport DPS. 
      
      There is no guarantee of any or a substantial number of journeys within this contract.
      
      Providers must be able to offer a service within the boundaries of Bedford Borough and environs and must provide a service which is fully compliant with the Bedford Borough Council Driver and Passenger Assistant Code of Practice.  Taxi companies and drivers must be registered with Bedford Borough Council, and Passenger Assistants must be in possession of a valid badge from Bedford Borough Council.

column66: CEFAS24-54 Contract for installation of Remote Electronic Monitoring (REM) equipment on 119m large pelagic vessel
column67:
In the summer of 2023, the UK Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra) released a consultation on the wider use of Remote Electronic Monitoring (REM) on fishing vessels in English Waters (Remote electronic monitoring - Defra - Citizen Space). This consultation outlined a number of "priority fisheries", the first of which being pelagic vessels over 24m in length. The consultation also proposed a multi-stage approach, starting with a voluntary early adopter phase.
Following the consultation, Defra, alongside Cefas and the Marine Management Organisation (MMO) entered into discussions with a vessel for participation in the early adopter phase. During these discussions, it was agreed that a REM system will be installed on the vessel by a qualified marine engineer.
Requirement: Installation of REM equipment onboard the pelagic fishing vessel Frank Bonefaas, 119m in length, according to an installation plan which is available in the Bidder Pack. The fishing vessel is currently undergoing general maintenance in the port of Ijmuiden.
A summary of the equipment to be installed is given below:

Up to 14 cameras, both internal and external
o
These will be linked to 2 or more power over ethernet (PoE) switches

Global System for Mobile communication/4G Long Term Evolution (GSM/4GLTE) and Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) antenna (to be mounted externally)

2x rotational winch sensors on the aft deck

2x hydraulic sensors

A monitor, located on the bridge of the vessel

A central computer, located on the bridge of the vessel
Installation of all cabling for the REM system must be done by the Supplier. This is a core requirement for Cefas and Suppliers should not bid if they are not able to deliver this element. The use of Subcontractors for this element is acceptable however this must be arranged by the supplier and detailed clearly in the 'information to be provided by the tenderer'.
The equipment listed above, will be supplied by Cefas, and Cefas will provide all available manufacturers installation manuals or guidance documentation including installation and wiring guide. Additional items required to complete the full installation, including CAT6-S/FTP cable, CAT6A shielded cables and glands, will need to be supplied by the Supplier. These additional items will need to be of suitable quality to operate in the marine environment as defined in the applicable standards and regulations.

column66: Provision of Bio-CNG and Filling Station at York Way Depot
column67:
MARKET ENGAGEMENT NOTICE FOR PROVISION OF BIO-CNG FILLING STATION AND GAS SUPPLY FOR THE LONDON BOROUGH OF CAMDEN

The London Borough of Camden wishes to explore a range of options including potential infrastructure upgrades at Camden Council Fleet hub based at York Way Depot (Freight Lane, 7 York Way, London, N1C 4BE) to enable the Council to meet its objective of reducing its CO2 emissions. 
The site is owned by the council and Camden Accessible Travel Solutions (CATS) manages all fleet services from the depot. CATS are responsible for managing and maintaining the Councils fleet of approx. 300 vehicles, of which 13 vehicles use Bio-Compressed Natural Gas (CNG) as a fuel source.
The Council has its own Bio-CNG filling station at York Way Depot. The filling station and associated equipment was installed in 2018 by and is currently maintained by a third party, who have a contract in place to deliver the service up to mid-February 2025. 
The Council are therefore looking to engage with the market to seek information and request suppliers to advise on:
	potential installation of a new Bio-CNG fuel station
	potential upgrade of the existing Bio-CNG fuel station
	maintenance of Bio-CNG high pressure fuel station and associated equipment
	Provision/supply of Bio-CNG gas
The council also wishes to seek interest and engage with suppliers or other third-party organisations who currently own and operate a fleet of CNG vehicles.
If your organisation is interested in providing any element of the requirements or maintaining any of the associated equipment, please express your interest and/or request a Supplier Information Pack by emailing helene.berhane@camden.gov.uk. 
The Council are planning to hold an open day at York Way depot at 10:30am on 18th June 2024 so that potential suppliers and third-party organisation can visit the site in person, express an interest in delivering an element of the service and discuss the requirements and potential options further.  
If you would like to attend the open day then please confirm your attendance by emailing helene.berhane@camden.gov.uk.

column66: IT Flex Partners Services
column67:
1. Background information on The University of Manchester
      The University of Manchester is a place where research has a global impact, where students experience outstanding teaching and learning, helping them to develop into tomorrow's leaders, and where all activity is enriched by a commitment to social responsibility. 
      Manchester was the first and most eminent of England's civic universities. Today, we're part of the prestigious Russell Group of UK universities, with an international reputation for the highest level of research and teaching, as demonstrated by our position in the Academic Ranking of World Universities. In 2021 we were placed 35th in the world and fifth in the UK. 
      Looking ahead, it's our vision to be one of the world's leading universities and to be recognised globally for the excellence of our people, research, learning and innovations, and for the benefits we bring to society and the environment.  
      The University employs over 13,000 staff across 3 faculties plus professional services and plays a key role in the cultural life of the region through Manchester Museum, John Rylands Research Institute and Library, Jodrell Bank (UNESCO World Heritage Site) and Whitworth Art Gallery.   Our student community is one of the largest in the UK and at present we have more than 44,000 students studying at the University 
      This quality of research feeds into our taught courses, many of which are also designed to meet the needs of industry. We offer more than 1,000 degree programmes and receive more undergraduate applications than any other UK university.
      Further details on the University can be found at:
      http://www.manchester.ac.uk/discover/facts-figures/
      
      2. Background information on Project
      The University is looking to engage with third party suppliers to appoint strategic flex model partners to support the current in-house IT capability.  The scope of IT Services is wide reaching, across nine Lots, with approximately 400 University staff performing various roles across the IT end to end landscape.  This includes but is not limited to roles across the project and pre-project lifecycle, and resources who provide live support to keep our vast number of student and staff systems and applications operating efficiently.  Whilst the University delivers mainly waterfall projects, we also have a desire to move more formally to an Agile delivery methodology.  
      The IT Flex partners will complement existing in-house IT delivery teams with an appropriate Flex model to provide, at short notice, resources in the event that one or more of our IT team(s) require specific expertise or are unable to fully resource IT delivery or support commitments, this is to include agreement on delivery of works via statements of work and the potential for future ongoing Managed service provisions.
      
      3. Project Overview
      This tender exercise will be split into nine different Lots. These are:
      1. General IT Services
      2. Testin...

column66: RDE562: Natural Flood Management (NFM) Benefits estimation methodology
column67: Estimating the economic benefits of natural flood management (NFM) in a proportionate and nationally consistent way is challenging and remains a barrier to mainstreaming Natural Flood Management (NFM). Through a previous FCRM R&D project we worked with a supplier to develop a prototype tool to estimate both flood risk and wider environmental economic benefits. This tool provides a high-level analysis which will allow targeting of NFM to places with good NFM opportunity and potential for flood risk benefits and quantification of wider environmental benefits. The tool is reliant on England wide GIS analysis and an excel spreadsheet which combines this information with estimates of wider environmental benefits based on the values in the EHOV lite tool. Deliverables are expected to be England wide heat mapping, updates to the methodology and a report (suitable for publication) outlining; evidence behind the tool, methodology & areas for further future development. The primary customer for this tool is the NFM Programme who will use it as part of full business case development. It will also be used for shadow pipeline development and potentially to value the flood risk benefits of ELM. In the future it may also be adopted to support economic analysis for business cases for other NFM projects.

column66: CP2243-23 Business Support Framework 2023
column67:
Devon County Council (DCC) is reletting its Business Support Framework to deliver business support in the Devon area and other economic geographies, potentially including: the Heart of the South West (HotSW); the Great South West; and a new Combined Authority under devolution.\r
\r
The Business Support Framework is split into six Lots. Suppliers may bid for more than one Lot. \r
\r
Lot 1: Business support and growth - delivering holistic business support for all types of businesses and social enterprises at all stages of the business life cycle, including a comprehensive range of diagnostic support, subject-specific support, and essential growth and planning support. \r
\r
Lot 2: Academic investigation and evaluation support - undertaking bespoke analysis and research of sectors, business support need and programmes. Outputs from suppliers will include a mixture of written reports, research data, and appropriate visuals, as well as potential presentations to officers, members, associated boards, and other parties involved in any of the project work. \r
\r
Lot 3: Specialist business support - providing specialist services and business support across all sectors, including farming and agriculture, on a variety of topics unique to specific sectors or business development. Themes include diversity in business, green business support, business and family succession planning, routes to market and procurement, and technological and digital business support. \r
\r
Lot 4: Productivity and skills - providing support for developing a more productive and skilled workforce, including supporting employers and organisations to plan and invest well, develop leadership and management, support recruitment and retention, and identify training needs in addition to accessing appropriate qualifications and/or training.\r
\r
Lot 5: Farming and agricultural business support - providing support to farming and agricultural businesses at all stages of the business life cycle. Suppliers should be equipped to understand the opportunities for funding and farming practice and have a comprehensive knowledge of the sector in its broadest sense (which includes forestry, horticulture, aquaculture, regenerative land management, agri-tech and innovation). \r
\r
Lot 6: Marketing and communication support - providing specialist marketing and promotion support for business support programmes. Outputs from suppliers may include the creation and delivery of a multi-media marketing and communications campaign, supplying a comprehensive suite of multi-media assets, a communication and branding plan to drive traffic to sign-up pages, brand development, in addition to analysis and campaign reporting on targeting specific audience(s), trend analysis, market research, and campaign evaluation. \r


Additional information: 
The framework is commissioned and managed by DCC, acting as the lead and responsible body, but will also be available to Somerset Council, Members of the Devon and Cornwall Procurement Partnership (D&CPP), the Heart of the South West Local Enterprise Partnership (HotSW LEP), and the new Combined Authority under devolution. For funding that requires a quick turnaround, the Business Support Framework will facilitate the quick mobilisation of business support programmes with suppliers who have already been pre-approved.
Devon County Council will be hosting a virtual Tender Launch Event via Microsoft Teams on Wednesday 18th October, 13:00-14:30. This will be an opportunity to discuss the service provision, ask questions, and help bidders navigate around the tender documentation and the procurement process. This event will be recorded and will be uploaded to ProContract alongside the presentation shortly afterward. 

If you would like to attend this event, please complete the following Tender Launch Event form so that we can send you an invite link. NB: Each attendee must complete a form to receive an invitation. 

https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=gzehjWjLP0S7S5l_d_1b-4mLsw8gtztKu6HIP272CL5URTIwSTBEMVUyQTBISlozTlpIVDFUNzE4RC4u
The authority reserves the right to cancel the procurement process at any stage. The authority does not bind itself to accept the lowest or any tender, and reserve the right not to award a contract. The authority reserves the right to award the contract in part, or to call for new tenders should they consider this necessary. Economic operators remain responsible for all costs and expenses incurred by them or by any third party acting under instructions from them in connection with their participation in this procurement, whether incurred directly by them or their advisors or subcontractors and regardless of whether such costs arise as a consequence direct or indirect of any amendments to documents issued by the authority at any time, or as a consequence of the cancellation of the procurement by the authority. For the avoidance of doubt, the authority shall have no liability whatsoever to economic operators or their advisors or subcontractors, for any of their costs, including but not limited to those for any discussions or communications. Any contract(s) or agreement(s) entered into as a result of this contract notice shall be considered as a contract(s) or agreement(s) made under English law and subject to the exclusive jurisdiction of the English courts. If an economic operator considers that any information supplied by it during this procurement process is commercially sensitive or confidential in nature, this should be highlighted and the reasons for its sensitivity as well as the duration of that sensitivity specified. Economic operators should be aware that even where they have indicated that information is commercially sensitive, the authority may disclose it pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in response to a request for information where such disclosure is considered to be in the public interest. Please note that the receipt by any of the authority of any materials marked 'confidential' or equivalent shall not be taken to mean that the authority accepts any duty of confidence by virtue of that marking.
The procurement documents are available for unrestricted and full direct access, free of charge, at: https://www.supplyingthesouthwest.org.uk.

Additional information can be obtained from the abovementioned address.

Tenders or requests to participate must be submitted electronically via: https://www.supplyingthesouthwest.org.uk.
The framework arrangement will be awarded for an initial period of 24 months, finishing on the 6th February 2026. There is an option to extend this framework arrangement for a further period totalling 24 months, finishing on the 6th February 2028.

column66: Cultural Service benefit indicators
column67:
PLEASE NOTE - contract value of up to 49,999 is exclusive of VAT

Natural England are seeking to develop the natural capital indicators approach to improve how benefits from cultural services are included. We are particularly interested in defining indicators that make use of qualitative information on how people benefit from the environment through non-material benefits, and how to link these benefits with the condition of the natural environment. We want to improve the way that benefits from cultural services can be included in place-based applications of natural capital; developing a deeper understanding to determine and define indicators that link natural capital asset condition (quality, quantity and location) with a range of benefits derived from cultural ecosystem services. This work includes desk-based scoping and research alongside focus groups with specialists and advisors. It will result in a suite of proposed indicators and their supporting data, and an interpretation package that details how to collect, use and apply the findings of the research in local-scale natural capital applications.

Additional information: To apply for this opportunity you must submit your quotation meeting the requirements detailed in the Request for Quotation (RFQ) attached.
Your response must be sent to caitlin.hinson@naturalengland.org.uk by 12 midday on Friday 21 June.

If you have any clarification questions linked to this opportunity or the procurement process please submit these via email to caitlin.hinson@naturalengland.org.uk. Please note that, unless commercially sensitive, both the question and the response will be circulated to all tenderers.

column66: Dynamic Purchasing System for the provision of Alternative Education
column67:
Kingsmead School in Derby has a statutory duty to make arrangements for the provision of suitable education otherwise than at school for children of compulsory school age who, by reason of exclusion from school or otherwise, will not receive a suitable education without these arrangements.

Derby City Council, on behalf of Kingsmead School, now  wishes to invite applications for inclusion on a Dynamic Purchasing System (DPS) for these services. By creating a DPS we will give Kingsmead School the flexibility of allowing new organisations to join at any time over the course of the DPS, subject to them meeting the initial suitability criteria which  will be set out in the DPS.

All service requirements over the course of the DPS will then be tendered by way of mini-competition, allowing all  organisations on the DPS at that time the opportunity to bid for the requirements at what would be a market appropriate rate at that time.  

Other Free Schools, Academies and Independent Schools within the city of Derby may also access the DPS with the support of Kingsmead School. 

The DPS will operate from 01/06/2018 and is currently expected to run to 31/05/2025.

This notice advises that Round Thirty Nine is now open and closes 10:00am 31/07/2024 with applications assessed by 31/08/2024. 

Further rounds will operate on a similar two monthly basis. 

An EU Light Touch procurement tender exercise which is compliant with the Public Contract Regulations 2015 will be undertaken to select providers for the DPS which will offer access to pre-approved DPS Providers who can be appointed using an efficient and streamlined procurement process; therefore ensuring the Council obtains value for money whilst enabling objectives to be achieved.
 
For clarity, this DPS is not a full DPS as defined under the Public Contract Regulations 2015, Regulation 34, but is a modified version. This is because Section 7 - Education and Training services (the Light Touch Regime as allowed under Regulations 74 to 77) are not subject to the full regulations of the procurement procedures set out in the Regulations.

Additional information: Further documentation is available at: 
	https://www.eastmidstenders.org.   

	If you haven't already registered on the e-tendering system, you will need to do so (link under "Welcome")
	Once registered, Click 'view opportunities' then 'search latest opportunities';
	Click on the contract title (DN328895 - TD1241 - Dynamic Purchasing System for the provision of Alternative Education 
	Click 'register interest'.  You can then access the DPS documentation through clicking on "My Opportunities" then the relevant contract. 

Expressions of interest and applications will only be accepted through the above tendering portal.

1.	Beaversfield Park:
The project consists of the following SuDS and landscaping features:
o	800 m of attenuation volume provided through below ground natural aquifer drainage stone wool blocks, located within Beaversfield Park
o	The area above the feature will incorporate an "Active & Play" landscape design, comprising of a pump track and terraced steps for seating. The area will have surrounding stone pathways and grass mound with predominantly meadow planting, providing additional amenity and public value. The landscape design adheres to the overall park masterplan.

The SuDS feature is designed to attenuate flows from the upstream catchment area for rainfall events up to and including 1 in 30-year return period including and allowance for climate change. 

2. Wellington Road North:
The project consists of the following SuDS features:
o	585m of below ground crate storage located within the green open space adjacent to Wellington Road North.
o	The area above the feature will incorporate a "Community-centric Corridor" landscape design, comprising large grass mounds, footpaths, and seating area. The area will have predominantly meadow planting and relocating existing tress, providing additional amenity and public value.

The SuDS feature is designed to fully attenuate flows from the upstream catchment area for rainfall events up to and including 1 in 10-year return period including, with exceedance flows occurring in storm events larger than for the 1 in 10-year return period events.

column66: PS23306 Evaluation framework and baseline evaluation for the Net Zero domain
column67:
***** THIS IS AN AWARD NOTICE, NOT A CALL FOR COMPETITION 

This procurement is being concluded following a mini competition under the Crown Commercial Services DPS RM6126 - Research & Insights.

Brief Description of Requirement

This procurement is part of ongoing work in building an evidence base to understand the effectiveness and impact obtained through Innovate UK interventions. 

This project is the first phase of ongoing work to demonstrate how Innovate UK Net Zero domain activities have made or will make an impact in each of the following areas:

	Environmental impacts - including but not limited to greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions directly or indirectly reduced as a consequence of Innovate UK programmes.
	Economic impacts - including but not limited to Gross Value Add (GVA), increased turnover, increased innovation spend, employment and exports.
	Business level innovation - including but not limited to innovation activity and capabilities, co-investment or follow-on investment UK positioning in key technologies.
	Commercialisation - including readiness levels (TRL, MRLs) and Intellectual Property.
	Capabilities - including skills

The aims of this project are to:

(i)	Establish a detailed monitoring and evaluation framework for the Innovate UK Net Zero domain that identifies a feasible plan, along with suitable metrics, to measure all outcomes of the Net Zero domain (i.e., environmental, economic, business level innovation, commercialisation, capabilities). This framework will also identify ongoing monitoring and performance reporting structures that establish datasets for an impact evaluation in later phases.
(ii)	To establish a baseline for the environmental impacts already identified across Net Zero domain reporting, by considering the existing reporting or data availability that could inform Net Zero domain programmes outcomes as well as the data availability and scale of secondary data sources. Reporting on the Net Zero domain also includes environmental benefits and impacts delivered by a different governance structure - the Healthy Living and Agriculture domain.

column66: Osiers Bridge (0305), Braunstone - West Parapet Upgrade
column67:
Contract award for the undertaking the Parapet upgrade work of A563 Osiers Bridge (0305), Braunstone, Leicester. The works requirement is led by the Structures and Street Lighting team within Leicestershire County Council.

The project involves:
 Removal of the existing 1m high metal parapet (West side only) and replace with N2 W2 1.5m high metal parapet to accommodate a dedicated cycleway.
 The bridge carries the A563 Lubbesthorpe way over A5460, junction 21 approach near Braunstone in Leicester.
 The scheme is to be carried out under a lane closure (on top) which will be designed and installed by Leicestershire County Council to include temporary vehicle restraint system to protect working area.

Required works:
 Installation of edge protection system (Combisafe or similar).
 Taking down and disposing of the existing metal parapet and transition sections as per drawing MC0305/01.
 Removing any protruding bolts from the parapet edge beam and making good the existing concrete.
 Drilling and resin-fixing anchorages for the new parapet posts.
 Installing new N2/W2 1.5m high parapet system.
 Installation of transition sections between the new parapet and the existing road restraint system (OBB).

column66: GB-Shrewsbury, Shropshire: DONV 039 - River Severn Catchment Cellular Mobile Network Coverage Study
column67:
The River Severn Partnership Advanced Wireless Innovation Region (RSPAWIR) aims to encourage the adoption of advanced wireless technologies by businesses and organisations across the River Severn catchment area.  The RSPAWIR is investing in Use Cases to demonstrate the possibilities and benefits of adopting wireless technologies with the aim that businesses and organisations across the region will use the experience to adopt themselves.  A critical part of that decision-making process is understanding the local commercial cellular mobile network availability.  This can be difficult as most of the public domain data that does exist around mobile coverage is aggregated and modelled which often undermines its value.  
      The RSPAWIR is looking to remedy this issue by commissioning an independent study of coverage across Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Monmouthshire, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Telford and Wrekin, Warwickshire and Worcestershire.  Powys has recently commissioned a similar study and is therefore not part of this procurement.  The study should be conducted primarily as a physical drive trial, rather than aggregating data generated via 3rd party apps and  the partners aim to understand the real-world coverage of all four main commercial mobile networks.  
      This intelligence will be used to;
      1.Inform decision makers within local businesses and organisations regarding the optimal network operator to support the adoption and operation of advanced wireless technologies; and
      2.Lobby Mobile Network Operators, UK Government departments and Ofcom on how to improve services (both 4G and 5G) where coverage is poor.
      The RSPAWIR are seeking the services of a commercial partner to 
      1.Either work with various Local Authority fleet operators to undertake a Drive Trial of the entire River Severn Catchment Area and its constituent counties (excluding Powys) or commission private drive trials to achieve the same result.
      2.Determine the actual on-street mobile signals for 4G and 5G from all 4 MNOs. 
      3.Enable businesses and organisations to undertake their own surveys of off-street locations including farm estates.
      4.Present the data generated to the procurement partners in aggregated form and to local businesses and organisations via online location-based requests.

Additional information: For more information about this opportunity, This intelligence will be used to;
        1.Inform decision makers within local businesses and organisations regarding the optimal network operator to support the adoption and operation of advanced wireless technologies; and
        2.Lobby Mobile Network Operators, UK Government departments and Ofcom on how to improve services (both 4G and 5G) where coverage is poor.
        The RSPAWIR are seeking the services of a commercial partner to 
        3.Either work with various Local Authority fleet operators to undertake a Drive Trial of the entire River Severn Catchment Area and its constituent counties (excluding Powys) or commission private drive trials to achieve the same result.
        4.Determine the actual on-street mobile signals for 4G and 5G from all 4 MNOs. 
        5.Enable businesses and organisations to undertake their own surveys of off-street locations including farm estates.
        6.Present the data generated to the procurement partners in aggregated form and to local businesses and organisations via online location-based requests.
        Please note the performance of this contract will be across Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Monmouthshire, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Telford and Wrekin, Warwickshire and Worcestershire

column66: GB-Colchester: 0379 - Heating Renewals for Housing Stock
column67:
This contract is for the Planned Replacement of Boilers and Heating Systems under the Housing Investment Programme for Colchester City Council's residential properties. 
      
      Colchester City Council's housing stock of approximately 6,100 tenanted units and 1000 leaseholder units is managed by Colchester Borough Homes Ltd, which is an Arm's Length Management Organisation, and will act as Contract Administrator for this contract.
      
      The Contract Administrator will provide the Contractor with a list of the properties identified in the annual programme. The properties are likely to be spread throughout the borough of Colchester and the Contractor will need to take this into consideration when pricing these works. The list may be added to/deducted from as necessary.
      
      The Contractor shall carry out a pre-works survey of all properties in the annual programme. The purpose of the pre-works survey is twofold. The Contractor needs to identify any risk or issues peculiar to the property and consider the needs of vulnerable residents when undertaking these works. The Contractor needs to ensure that the resident is aware and understands the scope of works and agrees any design or layout choices. The resident should be provided with contact details, emergency contact details, a description of the works to be undertaken and an indication as to the sequencing of these operations.
      
      The Contractor shall provide a dedicated, named Residents' Liaison person, who shall provide information and support to residents during the Works and will communicate the Contractor's operational activities and requirements in order to minimise the disruption to the residents.
      
      The product specification may be subject to change throughout the duration of the Contract if required for budgetary purposes.
      
      Further details of the requirements can be found in the accompanying documents.

Additional information: The contracting authority considers that this contract may be suitable for economic operators that are small or medium enterprises (SMEs). However, any selection of tenderers will be based solely on the criteria set out for the procurement.
        
        Costs shown are for year 1 only, as contract is subject to satisfactory performance for years 2-4.
        
        
        
        The anticipated contract start date is 1st June 2024 and will commence for 12 months until 31st May 2025.  With the option of two extension periods, the first of 1 year (1st June 2025-31st May 2026) and the second of 2 years (1st June 2026 -31st May 2028)  which will be subject to satisfactory performance and annual uplifts in accordance with the terms of this contract.
